  ##Check to make sure you don't have any errors
sudo /usr/local/nagios/bin/nagios -v /usr/local/nagios/etc/nagios.cfg

sudo vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/cgi.cfg

Authenticated user : Someone who has been authenticated to the web server with valid credentials [username and password] and granted access tot he Nagios interface.

Authenticated Contact: An authenticated user whose username matches a username in the contact definition


authorized_for_all_services=nagiosadmin
authorized_for_all_hosts=nagiosadmin



htpasswd /usr/local/nagios/etc/htpasswd.users demo


sudo vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/cgi.cfg

	authorized_for_all_services=nagiosadmin,demo
	authorized_for_all_hosts=nagiosadmin,demo

sudo systemctl restart nagios


Turning Authentication off : All authentication can be turend off! This is obviously not recommended but it can be done.

Creating a View-Only Account: This type of account can see all the hosts and services but does not have the ability to make any changes

Ceating a system Administrator Account: The user will have full acces to all hosts and services, But because the user is not a contact and is not a member of any contact list. they will not receive any notifications.

Limiting Administrator Account Access: The administrator use will be a contact and have contact information. As a result, it will only be able to access hosts and servers that the contact associated with

cd /usr/local/nagios/etc/

	htpasswd htpasswd.users Raja
	password:

sudo vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/cgi.cfg
	
	authorized_for_all_service_commands=nagiosadmin,raja
	authorized_for_all_host_commands=nagiosadmin,raja
	
	authorized_for_read_only=raja
	
	systemctl restart nagios
	systemctl restart httpd
